---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base
  path="/about"
  title="About Anthem Music | Music Lessons in McKinney, TX"
  description="Anthem Music is a family-centered studio in downtown McKinney, founded by a self-taught guitarist with 35+ years of playing and 15+ years of teaching. Real instruction, built from hundreds of students."
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow" style="justify-content:center;">Our Story</span>
      <h1 class="center">More than a lesson studio</h1>
      <p class="lead mx-auto center">Anthem Music is a family-centered studio in downtown McKinney where students of every age are welcomed, taught real musicianship, and encouraged to make music that's their own.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="body-lg">Anthem started the way a lot of good things do - with someone who learned the hard way and wanted to make the road a little easier for the next person. This is our founder's story, in his own words.</p>

      <h2>How it began</h2>
      <p>I was twelve when my dad bought me my first guitar. It wasn't the electric I wanted - it was a budget-friendly classical, and if I was serious about playing, I had to prove it. So I sat in my room with the only two music books I had - a Led Zeppelin songbook and a book of chords - and I played them until I'd earned that electric.</p>
      <p>Guitar wasn't even my first instrument. I'd spent a few years in school band on tuba, French horn, and trumpet - first chair trumpet, eventually - so the formal training was there. I could read music and hold a part. But guitar was different. Guitar was mine.</p>
      <p>We lived in the country, and the nearest music store was almost an hour away in Plano. When a string broke, sometimes it just stayed broken. My guitar seldom had all six strings - even today, I catch myself avoiding the high E, because the guitar I learned on almost never had one.</p>
      <p>This was 1986. There was no YouTube or smartphone waiting to show me how a song was supposed to be played. I listened, figured things out by ear, and did the best I could. Sometimes I got it right. Sometimes I didn't. My twelve-year-old son occasionally learns a song today and informs me that I've been playing it wrong for forty years - and sometimes, he's right.</p>
      <p>But the learning never stopped. I'm still learning today.</p>
      <p>When I began teaching, I wanted to shorten that road for my students. I started by sketching chords and notes on scratch paper. Those became worksheets, then better diagrams and clearer explanations, built around the questions my students were actually asking. Over the years, hundreds of students helped shape those pages into the method book that remains a cornerstone of our program today.</p>
      <p>And it's still evolving. Just about every week I'm adding something, changing something, or creating a new worksheet because one particular student needs a different way to understand one particular thing.</p>

      <h2>The long road back to music</h2>
      <p>Music wasn't a straight path for me. I served in the Air Force in the early 1990s - I'm a Gulf War veteran - and when I returned home, I worked and went to school. At some point I felt I had to choose between business and music. I didn't think I could support a family strumming a guitar, so I chose business.</p>
      <p>I spent nearly twenty years in corporate IT and built a successful career. But I never really left music. I kept playing gigs. I kept teaching. No matter where my career took me, I always found my way back.</p>
      <p>Then, right before Covid, I was preparing to spend several months out of state leading a technology project. My son, about six at the time, said something I'll never forget:</p>
      <blockquote class="kid-quote"><p>&ldquo;Dad, you leave before I get up in the morning, and you're not home until after I go to bed. I never get to see you.&rdquo;</p></blockquote>
      <p>That changed everything. I left the corporate world and built Anthem. I knew it would be scary, and I knew money would be tighter - but being present for my children mattered more to me than any corporate job ever could.</p>
      <p>Anthem let me build a life around something I love while staying connected to the people and community I care about - more than twelve years coaching youth sports, volunteering in my kids' schools, serving on the PTO, and these days running concessions for every Dowell Athletic Booster Club game. McKinney isn't just where I opened a music studio. It's home.</p>

      <h2>What we believe</h2>
      <p>My number one rule is simple: <strong>music should bring you joy, first and foremost.</strong></p>
      <p>I didn't always teach that way. My students taught me. Over the years I've learned that my job isn't to turn every student into the musician I am. Some want to understand every scale and mode on the neck. Some couldn't care less about theory. Some want to perform, some want to write - and some just want to learn a few songs they love and send me a video at midnight because they finally got one right. Those are all worthy goals.</p>
      <p>If the music sounds good to you, makes you happy, and keeps you playing, then it's good. My job is to help you get wherever you want music to take you.</p>
      <p>Most programs teach students to copy - to learn songs and techniques by imitation. That's the foundation, and it matters. But we don't stop there. We take students through the whole arc: <em>copy, create, and innovate</em> - from playing other people's music cleanly to writing and playing music that's genuinely their own.</p>
      <p>Mastering an instrument is a lifelong endeavor, and we're honest about that. There's no shortcut that replaces sitting across from an experienced teacher who can see what you're doing and tell you how to get better. That's what we do - for guitar, piano, violin, drums, brass, and more.</p>
      <p>One more thing you should know about us: you'll never get a flat "we don't do that" here. We've built a trusted network of teaching partners across the local music community, and if a teacher at another studio better aligns with your goals - say, a full band or orchestra program - we'll set up a consultation with them ourselves. Getting you to the right fit matters more to us than keeping you in the wrong seat.</p>
      <p class="signoff">- Dan Brady, Founder</p>

      <div class="values">
        <div class="value">
          <h3>Craft</h3>
          <p>Music is a real skill worth learning well. We teach it that way - clear fundamentals, honest feedback, high standards.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="value">
          <h3>Mentorship</h3>
          <p>Our instructors are mentors, not just teachers. Students are formed over time, and we meet each one where they are.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="value">
          <h3>Community</h3>
          <p>A family-centered place in downtown McKinney where students build confidence, discipline, and a lifelong love of music.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cta-band">
    <div class="container cta-inner">
      <div>
        <h2>Come see for yourself</h2>
        <p>Book a lesson and experience the Anthem approach firsthand.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/schedule" class="btn btn-primary">Book a Consultation</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .page-hero { background: var(--cream-soft); padding: clamp(2.5rem,5vw,4rem) 0; }
  .page-hero h1 { margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .narrow { max-width: 760px; }
  .body-lg { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--navy); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 2.5rem; font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 400; }
  .narrow h2 { margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem; }
  .narrow p { color: var(--gray); margin-bottom: 1.2rem; }
  .narrow p em { color: var(--orange); font-style: italic; }
  .narrow p strong { color: var(--navy); }
  .kid-quote { margin: 1.6rem 0; padding: 0.3rem 0 0.3rem 1.2rem; border-left: 3px solid var(--orange); }
  .kid-quote p { color: var(--navy); font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.15rem; line-height: 1.55; margin: 0; }
  .signoff { color: var(--navy); font-weight: 600; margin-top: 2rem; }
  .values { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3,1fr); gap: 1.5rem; margin-top: 3rem; }
  .value { background: var(--cream-soft); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.8rem; }
  .value h3 { color: var(--navy); margin-bottom: 0.6rem; }
  .value p { color: var(--gray); font-size: 0.95rem; margin: 0; }

  .cta-band { background: var(--orange); padding: clamp(2.5rem,5vw,4rem) 0; }
  .cta-inner { display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between; gap: 2rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .cta-band h2 { color: var(--white); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
  .cta-band p { color: var(--white); opacity: 0.92; max-width: 46ch; }
  .cta-band .btn-primary { background: var(--white); color: var(--orange-dark); }
  .cta-band .btn-primary:hover { background: var(--navy); color: var(--cream); }

  @media (max-width: 700px) { .values { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
</style>
